  "prompt": "What are good, low-cost (or free) alternatives to Google Alerts?",
  "response": "There are several low-cost or free alternatives to Google Alerts that can help you monitor the web for specific keywords, news, or topics. Here are some options:\n\n1. **Talkwalker Alerts**: This free service provides alerts for news, blogs, and discussions online. You can set up alerts for specific keywords and receive notifications via email.\n\n2. **Mention**: Mention offers a free plan with limited features. You can track brand mentions, keywords, and competitors across social media and the web.\n\n3. **Feedly**: While primarily an RSS feed aggregator, Feedly allows you to follow relevant blogs, news sites, and sources for specific keywords. The free version provides basic capabilities.\n\n4. **Yahoo Alerts**: Similar to Google Alerts, you can set up custom alerts on Yahoo for news and topics of interest. While it\u2019s not as comprehensive as Google Alerts, it\u2019s still a viable option.\n\n5. **IFTTT (If This Then That)**: This automation tool allows you to set up custom alerts based on various triggers. You can connect different services and receive notifications via email or text.\n\n6. **Buzzsumo**: While primarily a content research tool, Buzzsumo allows you to set up alerts for specific keywords and monitor content trends. They have a free trial, but the ongoing use may require a paid plan.\n\n7. **Social Search**: A simple tool that helps you track social media mentions, providing alerts for topics or keywords you care about.\n\n8. **Boardreader**: This is a search engine for forums and message boards. While it doesn\u2019t send alerts, it does help track discussions around specific topics.\n\n9. **RSS Feeds**: Many websites and blogs offer RSS feeds, which can be monitored using an RSS reader (like Feedly or Inoreader). You can set alerts based on new articles and updates.\n\n10. **Twitter Lists & Hashtags**: Creating specific Twitter lists or following certain hashtags can help you stay updated on real-time discussions and news related to your topics of interest.\n\nEach of these alternatives has unique features, so consider what best fits your needs in terms of functionality and ease of use.",
